      <byline class="print_byline">By SAM LUBELL</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Lubell, Sam</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Swedish jeweler Anika Salame moves her accessory and jewelry boutique from Los Angeles to Manhattan's East 78th Street (New Yorkers &amp; Co column) (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Anika Salame, originally from Sweden, has lived in the United States for 10 years, in Miami, New York and Los Angeles. Moving her boutique, Anika, which sells fashion accessories and jewelry, here from Los Angeles last month, she finally decided to stay in the city. ''I just prefer New York,'' Ms. Salame says. ''There's a lot more of everything here.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Anika Salame, originally from Sweden, has lived in the United States for 10 years, in Miami, New York and Los Angeles. Moving her boutique, Anika, which sells fashion accessories and jewelry, here from Los Angeles last month, she finally decided to stay in the city. ''I just prefer New York,'' Ms. Salame says. ''There's a lot more of everything here.''</p>
        <p>Ms. Salame's store, which she opened with her husband, Philippe, offers a lot as well. The boutique on 243 East 78th Street, between Second and Third Avenues, sells one-of-a-kind costume and silver jewelry made by Ms. Salame, from $30 to $50. Also inside the modern store are accessories by New York designers like Isomar and Nicole Miller. Bags are $85 to $225.</p>
        <p>NEW YORKERS &amp; CO.</p>
      </block>
